My first instinct when I hear a small guild, is a guild with maybe 40 members that are levels 50 to 60 and the majority of those low 50s.  I'm thinking of a pre-HoT guild that is still having raids in KD for gear, and Sev is the only rotation mob it can kill.  However, &quot;small&quot; is not a good term for this becuase a guild of 12 people, that are all level 65, could be considered small and could mobilize quite easily against Sev at any given time.  So for lack of a better term, lets call this type of guild a &quot;hoodlie&quot; guild.<br>
<br>
If a guild is forced to pass after two guilds beat it onto a rotation, then I think these hoodlie guilds would most likely be the ones ending up having to pass.  The 24 hour window to kill Sev was set up for these hoodlie guilds to allow them to kill the mob in their prime time.  This is becuase the hoodlie guild can only manage the force capable to kill Sev during its prime time.  To force a hoodlie guild to pass, Sev would have to spawn and be killed twice in a row, each time before the guild's prime time.<br>
<br>
There are many guilds out there that have the members and the levels to kill Sev at any moment of the day.  These guilds don't have to wait for their prime time.  They only have to send out a small force to take out the mob.  Now how often do you think these guilds will be forced to pass on Sev?<br>
<br>
One of the main purposes of rotations is to give guilds, who would normally get &quot;out raced&quot;, the oppurtuntity to kill highly desired mobs.  If Sev was FFA, Hoodlie guilds would be the guilds that would get out raced.  By making a forced pass rule, you would be making it more difficult for them to participate in the rotation which in turn nullifies one of the main purposes of having a rotation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hutterr>Hutterr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fallen Shadows</span><br>  Posts: 108<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(12/5/02 5:57:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm15.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=887.topic&index=63>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Rotation Rules?</span><hr size=1> I have to agree with rogg on every point. This really has become more of a heated issue than it needs to be.<br>
<br>
Sev, in my opinion is simply the first (because its the easiest) rot mob to see this problem. It wont be the last. More and more guilds are becoming strong enough to enter various rotations.<br>
<br>
The &quot;new&quot; system as it has been suggested would not limit content for anyone. Its sole purpose is the exact opposite. If guild A is up and loses a &quot;race&quot; once, then they know they HAVE to be ready the next week. If they are busy &quot;frying bigger (or different) fish&quot; perhaps they should think about scheduling the bigger fish around their rotation obligations.<br>
<br>
I wouldnt even be opposed to allowing 2 guilds per &quot;turn&quot; to enter without penalty, but guild A MUST kill on the third spawn or lose their turn. If 10 guilds enter all at once, the practicality of the rotation is destroyed because NO ONE can plan for their kill.<br>
<br>
Im all for new guilds entering rotation (as we're not on Sev yet), but I dont want my guild to enter the alliance as one of many holding back people who have been planning for a month to finally get their epic. If I push em back a week cause im the only guild jumpin in, so be it, but 3 or 4+ weeks is a little rediculous. If a guild on a rotation loses that many times, it seems fairly obvious that its not much of a priority for them. <br>
<br>
The chances of an &quot;off time&quot; spawn 2 (or 3 as I said before) weeks in a row where other 24/7 guilds that arent already on rotation are ready is so unbelievably slim its not funny. Im a guild with about 50 members, 40 of which are 50+ in an alliance with guilds that bring our numers up to around 100. We couldnt take Sev at 8AM EST either, so there is one fairly powerful small to mid end guild/alliance you dont need to worry about. I assure you most of us ready for Sev are in the same boat.<br>
<br>
Im not sure if this lends any credence to the argument, but *IM* the one youre defending Abaz, and Rogg's arguments make more sense. No need to be upset, but we have rules that force a timely kill already for the purpose of moving things along, why would it be wrong to have rules to enforce that a guild progress the rotation? <p>Hutterr Verbruggen<br>
